'''Kalma''' is the [[Finnish folklore|Finnish goddess]] of [[death]] and [[Decomposition|decay]], her name meaning "The Stench of Corpses".<ref name=checker>{{cite web|title=KALMA|url=http://www.godchecker.com/pantheon/finnish-mythology.php?deity=KALMA|publisher=www.godchecker.com|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref> Her favorite places to linger are graveyards and cemeteries; in fact, one Finnish word for graveyard is ''kalmisto'', derived from her name. Some sources state that she moves on a vehicle of odors, much like a puff of smoke.<ref name=checker/>

Her father is [[Tuoni]] and her mother [[Tuonetar]]. Kalma may also have several sisters, Kipu-Tyttö, Kivutar, [[Loviatar]], and [[Vammatar]], all of whom live in the Finnish [[underworld]] realm of [[Tuonela]]. Kalma is accompanied and protected by [[Surma (Finnish mythology)|Surma]], a dog-like creature whose name literally means ''death" (though the word "surma" is usually used to refer to someone being killed, as opposed to dying of natural causes)'.<ref name=angel>{{cite web|title=TUONI|url=http://www.angelfire.com/planet/mythguide/tuoni.html|publisher=www.angelfire.com|accessdate=8 November 2012}}</ref>

Their stories are recited in the Finnish national epic [[Kalevala]].

