The '''Qasr el Sagha Formation'''is a [[formation (geology)|geological]] formation located in [[Egypt]]<ref>{{Harvnb|Vickers-Rich|Rich|1993}}</ref> ({{Coord|29.7|30.8|display=inline}}, paleocoordinates,{{Coord|25.0|26.7|display=inline}}). It dates to the [[Late Eocene]] (middle [[Priabonian]],{{Mya|37.2|33.9}}).<ref>{{Paleodb|79699|Tamariskenbucht (Eocene of Egypt)}}. Retrieved July 2013.</ref>
Fossils of the [[Archaeoceti|early whale]] genus ''[[Saghacetus]]'' ("Sagha whale", originally named "''Zeuglodon osiris''") were first collected at Qasr al Sagha by German explorer [[Georg August Schweinfurth]] in January 1886 (a well-preserved dentary).''Saghacetus'' is common in the middle of Qasr el Sagha, but there are few other specimens of archaeocetes whales; the only exception being the enigmatic "''Prozeuglodon stromeri''", named in 1828 based on specimens from 1904, but never adequately described before their destruction during the [[Bombing of Munich in World War II|bombing of Munich]] in [[World War II]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Gingerich|2007|pp=363–4}}</ref>
