{{Politics of Swaziland}}
'''General elections''' were held in [[Swaziland]] on 20 September 2013.<ref>http://africajournalismtheworld.com/2013/06/05/swaziland-election-set-for-20-september/</ref>
==Background== The primary elections began on 24 August, 2013 with one candidate elected from each chiefdom. Those elected then go on to represent the chiefdom in the general election, where one candidate from each [[Inkhundla]] (constituency) is then elected to the House of Assembly.<ref name=Board-Defeated>{{cite web|title=Swaziland: Election Board Defeated in High Court|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201308250246.html|work=www.allafrica.com|publisher=AllAfrica Global Media|accessdate=August 27, 2013|date=August 24, 2013}}</ref>
Some political analysts have voiced concerns that women are being prevented from participating in the primary elections. In one case, a nominated candidate was disqualified because she was wearing trousers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Phakathi|first=Mantoe|title=Swazi Chiefs Shut Women Out of Parliament|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2013/08/swazi-chiefs-shut-women-out-of-parliament/|work=www.ipsnews.net|publisher=IPS-Inter Press Service|accessdate=August 27, 2013|date=August 21, 2013}}</ref> The High Court later ordered the Elections and Boundaries Commission (EBC) to add her name back to the ballot.<ref name=Board-Defeated /> However, some residents from her chiefdom threatened to boycott the elections, complaining that she had not been properly nominated.<ref name=Election-Shambles>{{cite web|title=Swaziland: Swazi Primary Election Shambles|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201308250241.html|work=www.allafrica.com|publisher=AllAfrica Global Media|accessdate=August 27, 2013|date=August 25, 2013}}</ref>
==Electoral system== About 415,000 were registered to vote for the 55 of 65 seats in the [[House of Assembly of Swaziland|House of Assembly]]. The other ten seats are to be filled by nominees from King [[Mswati III]] when he selects his cabinet and Prime Minister.<Ref name="aljaz"/>
==Campaign== As a result of the presence of a number of reform candidates, there was speculation of a more inclusive government by the traditionalists. However, the banned opposition groups such as the [[Pudemo]] party and the South Africa-based [[Swaziland Solidarity Network]] called for a boycott.<ref name="aljaz">http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2013/09/201392034529659842.html</ref>
